      { name: "Ezetimibe (Zetia)", type: "Cholesterol Absorption Inhibitor", action: "Selectively inhibits Niemann-Pick C1-Like 1 (NPC1L1) protein in the jejunal brush border, blocking intestinal absorption of dietary and biliary cholesterol by ~50%. Reduces LDL-C by 15-20% as monotherapy and provides additional 23-24% reduction when added to statin (complementary mechanisms). Does NOT affect triglycerides or HDL significantly", sideEffects: "Generally very well tolerated. Diarrhea, abdominal pain (uncommon), myalgia (rare, may increase statin-associated myopathy slightly), hepatitis (very rare with statin combination)", contra: "Moderate-severe hepatic impairment (with statin combination), pregnancy", pearl: "First add-on after maximally tolerated statin per ACC/AHA guidelines (IMPROVE-IT trial showed incremental CV benefit in ACS patients: NNT 50 over 7 years). No CYP interactions - safe with essentially all medications. Cost-effective now generic. Consider as alternative to higher-dose statin if side effects limit titration." }
